      "symbolism": "Moira symbolizes life's non-negotiable limits‚Äîdeath, aging, and certain key events cannot be avoided. The thread metaphor suggests life's fragility and measured duration. The Moirai's indifference to status (affecting gods and mortals) represents fate's democracy and justice. Moira embodies the Greek tragic vision: knowing one's fate doesn't permit escape, but facing destiny courageously demonstrates arete. The concept balances divine power (gods are mighty) with cosmic limits (even Zeus bows to fate), suggesting ultimate order transcends individual will. Moira represents the boundary between what we control (our response) and what we don't (our portion).",
      "culturalSignificance": "Moira shaped Greek literature, particularly tragedy where protagonists face inescapable fate. The concept influenced Western ideas of destiny, predestination, and the tragic hero. The Fates (Moirai) became archetypal figures appearing across Western literature and art. 'Fatal,' 'fatalism,' and 'fate' derive from this tradition. The tension between fate and free will remains central to Western philosophy and theology. Modern discussions of determinism versus agency echo ancient moira debates. The concept taught Greeks to accept the uncontrollable while still striving for excellence‚Äîa philosophy relevant to human limitation and mortality."
